interesting_discoveries.question: Q4
interesting_discoveries.detected_name: Incorrect handling of two numeric inputs on single line
interesting_discoveries.detected_description: The student attempts to read two double values (e.g., x1 and y1) from a single user input line by calling `nextDouble()` twice consecutively. This does not work as expected when the user enters both values on the same line, as the second `nextDouble()` call will attempt to read from the next token, which might not be available or might be the newline character, leading to odd input behavior or errors.

interesting_discoveries.question: Q4
interesting_discoveries.detected_name: Incorrect Scanner usage for paired inputs
interesting_discoveries.detected_description: The student attempts to read two double values (e.g., x1 and y1) on a single line of input without proper handling for how Scanner processes the input stream, especially when expecting a space or newline separator. This leads to the program waiting for a second input when only one has been provided on a line.

interesting_discoveries.question: Q4
interesting_discoveries.detected_name: Incorrect input parsing for multiple values on one line
interesting_discoveries.detected_description: The student's code expects two separate inputs (e.g., x1, then y1) when the prompt example shows both x and y being entered on a single line (e.g., '00'). The `nextDouble()` method reads only one numeric value at a time, leaving the rest of the line unread, which can lead to input mismatches or unexpected behavior if the user types two numbers on one line.
